Jim Gilbert wrote:

&gt;Fredrik and Ron,
&gt;
&gt;These are often referred to as Nagoya-mono.  It&#39;s a kind of shiiremono that
&gt;copied Mino/Goto style.  These fittings are often marketed as &quot;Mino Goto,&quot;
&gt;but the quality of the materials and workmanship is not at that level of
&gt;work.
&gt;
&gt;The problem is not that they have been cleaned, but that they are not made
&gt;out of shakudo.  This type of fitting is often coated with a thin black wash
&gt;to simulate shakudo, but that is often worn away from the seppa dai.  The
&gt;nanako is more coarse than would be seen in genuine Mino or Goto work.
&gt;Rather than using gold inlay/overlay a thin gold wash is used.  Where this
&gt;is rubbed on the high spots the underlying copper shows through.  The
&gt;quality of the carving is not at the level Mino or Goto work.
&gt;
&gt;As Ron says there is a continuum of this type of material ranging from very
&gt;poor to pretty good.  The distinction between lower quality Mino-bori and
&gt;higher quality Nagoya-mono can be pretty fuzzy.
&gt;
&gt;I doubt that the fuchigashira and tsuba are by the same person.  The details
&gt;of the carving of the peony  are quite different.  They are the same type of
&gt;work though.  They&#39;re probably from the late Edo period.  There are quite a
&gt;few wakizashi mounted with this style of tosogu.
&gt;
&gt;Jim
